/*!
\page mathfunctions_sind SIND Sine Degrees Function

<p>
Section: \ref sec_mathfunctions "Mathematical Functions"
\section Usage
Computes the sine of the argument, but takes
the argument in degrees instead of radians (as is the case
for <tt>cos</tt>). The syntax for its use is
\verbatim
   y = sind(x)
\endverbatim
\section Examples
The sine of 45 degrees should be <tt>sqrt(2)/2</tt>

\if FRAGMENT
frag_mathfunctions_sind_000.m
0
sind(45)
\endif


\verbinclude frag_mathfunctions_sind_000.m.out 

and the sine of <tt>30</tt> degrees should be 0.5:

\if FRAGMENT
frag_mathfunctions_sind_001.m
0
sind(30)
\endif


\verbinclude frag_mathfunctions_sind_001.m.out 

